.row.team-section
  h1 Team
  p 
    |Pop Up Archive began at the 
    a href="http://ischool.berkeley.edu" target="_blank" UC Berkeley School of Information
    |, which is known for its curriculum centered on technology-driven innovation and iterative design, and has produced numerous Bay Area startups. Pop Up Archive received multiple awards for Information Technology for Society from the 
    a href="http://bigideas.berkeley.edu/" target="_blank" Berkeley Big Ideas competition 
    | and is the winner of the 2012 
    a href="http://newschallenge.tumblr.com" target="_blank" John S. and James L. Knight Foundation News Challenge: Data
    |. Our team benefits from perspectives in information management, business, technology, radio, and public media. Team members and advisers come from the School of Information, the UC Berkeley Boalt School of Law, Silicon Valley, public media organizations, archives, standards-making bodies, and open-source software projects.

  ul
    li.team_bio
      img src="#{asset_path('team/anne_wootton2.png')}"
      h2 Anne Wootton
      h3 Co-founder, CEO
      p
        |Anne has worked with independent producers 
        a href="http://kitchensisters.org" target="_blank" The Kitchen Sisters 
        | and national grant agencies to identify preservation and access opportunities for independent radio. She holds a Master’s degree from the University of California Berkeley in Information Management and Systems, where she focused in digital archives and the sociology of technology. She contributed to the creation of 
        a href="http://disciplineoforganizing.org/" target="_blank" The Discipline of Organizing
        |, a textbook in use at I Schools nationwide that unites perspectives about organizing from engineering, library science, and other fields. She is a 2012 
        a href="https://blog.soundcloud.com/2012/10/26/fellows-conclusion/" target="_blank" Soundcloud Community Fellow 
        | and winner of the 2012 
        a href="http://newschallenge.tumblr.com" target="_blank" Knight News Challenge: Data
        |. Before arriving in California, Anne lived in France, and managed a historic 
        a href="http://dl.lib.brown.edu/dbdh/" target="_blank" newspaper digitization project 
        | at Brown University.
    li.team_bio
      img title="Bailey Smith" alt="Bailey Smith" src="#{asset_path('team/bailey_smith2.png')}" width="150" height="150"
      h2 Bailey Smith
      h3 Co-founder, CTO
      p 
        |Bailey holds a Master’s from the UC Berkeley School of Information in Information Management and Systems and has worked as an editor, journalist, web master and information architect. She has worked at Yahoo and contributed to projects as a user experience researcher and designer for 
        a href="http://codeforamerica.org/" target="_blank" Code for America 
        | and 
        a href="http://pivotallabs.com/" target="_blank" Pivotal Labs
        |. She has also engaged intimately with media production as a transmedia consultant and as the producer of the radio documentary, Local Hire, an exploration of the rise and fall of film production in North Carolina. Bailey is a 
        a href="https://blog.soundcloud.com/2012/10/26/fellows-conclusion/" target="_blank" 2012 Soundcloud Community Fellow 
        | and winner of the 2012 
        a href="http://newschallenge.tumblr.com" target="_blank" Knight News Challenge: Data
        |. 
    li.team_bio
      img title="Emily Saltz" alt="Emily Saltz" src="#{asset_path('team/emily_saltz.png')}" width="150" height="150"
      h2 Emily Saltz
      h3 Head of Content Strategy
      p 
        | Emily earned a B.A. with honors in Linguistics from UC Santa Cruz. While there, she got up close and personal with the speech formants as a research assistant in the Phonetics and Phonology Lab, also moonlighting as an eye-tracking technician in the Psycholinguistics Lab. A lifelong public media fangirl, she used episodes of "This American Life" to teach Russian students English when living in Saint Petersburg, Russia. She is the tweeter and blogger in residence at Pop Up Archive, and loves nothing more than finding audio gems from Pop Up's varied and ever-expanding collections.
        
    li.team_bio.no_round
      a href="http://prx.org" 
        img title="prx" alt="" src="#{asset_path('team/prx.png')}" width="150" height="54.5"
        h2 
          a href="http://prx.org" target="_blank" Public Radio Exchange
      p 
        a href="http://prx.org" target="_blank" The Public Radio Exchange (PRX) 
        | was formed in 2003 by the 
        a href="http://www.cpb.org" target="_blank" Corporation for Public Broadcasting
        | , the 
        a href="http://www.nea.gov/" target="_blank" National Endowment of the Arts
        | , and the 
        a href="http://www.fordfoundation.org/" target="_blank" Ford Foundation
        | . With over 130,000 members, today PRX stands as the primary web-based distribution platform for broadcast radio, where stations shop content and producers push content to the public. PRX’s development team is developing the Pop Up Archive web service and API, informed by their work on the 
        a href="http://publicmediaplatform.org/" target="_blank" Public Media Platform (PMP) 
        | and their experience developing mobile apps for numerous stations, 
        a href="http://www.thisamericanlife.org/" target="_blank" This American Life
        |, and 
        a href="http://www.radiolab.org/" target="_blank" Radiolab
        |.

